This article is a presidential proclamation by Barack Obama declaring August 26, 2010, as Women's Equality Day. The proclamation commemorates the ratification of the 19th Amendment to the Constitution, which granted women the right to vote. It acknowledges the progress made in achieving gender equality but also highlights the remaining inequalities, such as underrepresentation of women in Congress and leadership positions in companies, the gender pay gap, and barriers faced by women in science and engineering. The proclamation emphasizes the administration's commitment to advancing women's equality through initiatives like the White House Council on Women and Girls, the National Equal Pay Enforcement Task Force, and the Paycheck Fairness Act. It also mentions efforts to address gender-based violence and promote women's empowerment globally. The proclamation concludes by calling on the American people to celebrate women's achievements and work towards true gender equality.